nty years. David Biale traces Scholem's tumultuous life of political activism and cultural criticism, including his falling-out with Hannah Arendt over the Eichmann trial. Mining a rich trove of diaries, letters, and other writings, Biale shows that his subject's inner life illuminates his most important writings. Scholem emerges as a passionately engaged man of his times-a period that encompassed two world wars, the rise of Nazism, and the Holocaust.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Cultural Heritage.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2018z978311063899840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300235159423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780300235159.jpg  a978-3-11-063899-8  YUP eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles